    <has_dmc>No</has_dmc>
  </oversight_info>
  <brief_summary>
    <textblock>
      The purpose of this pilot study was to compare two devices and three methods for achieving&#xD;
      hemostasis after a transradial angiogram while assessing vascular complications and time&#xD;
      endpoints. The heart has traditionally been accessed through the femoral artery. However, in&#xD;
      the last 20 years, the radial artery has gained more popularity among physicians and&#xD;
      patients, thereby offering an alternative to the femoral approach. Various methods of&#xD;
      applying compression to the radial puncture site have been used, but no research has been&#xD;
      done to show what best practice is. In this case, best practice would be the most effective&#xD;
      way of getting hemostasis while limiting complications and ensuring the efficient use of&#xD;
      nursing and medical resources. It is hypothesized that statistically significant differences&#xD;
      are seen in time to discharge in the fast-release Terumo and Clo-Sur P.A.D. groups, as&#xD;
      compared with the control Terumo group, without increasing vascular complications.&#xD;
    </textblock>
  </brief_summary>
